                '# Special Character Encoding — Complete Reference\n\n> **Two different hazards.** (1) Characters that conflict with **Mermaid** syntax inside labels — encode them per the table below. (2) Characters that a **Markdown processor** corrupts in the diagram *source* when the diagram is embedded in a `.md` file — see "Markdown-embedding hazards" at the end. The second is what makes a diagram that renders fine standalone throw a syntax error inside a document.\n\n## Encoding Strategy\n\n1. **Always use quoted labels**: `["..."]`, `("...")`, `{"..."}`, etc.\n2. **Inside quoted labels**, most characters are safe\n3. **Encode ONLY characters that conflict** with the specific delimiter or Mermaid syntax\n4. **Format**: `#<decimal_code>;` — this is Mermaid\'s HTML entity syntax\n\n---\n\n## Complete Encoding Table\n\n### Characters That ALWAYS Need Encoding in Labels\n\nThese characters conflict with Mermaid\'s core syntax and must always be encoded when they appear inside labels:\n\n| Character | Name | Entity | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `"` | Double quote | `#34;` | `["She said #34;hello#34;"]` |\n| `<` | Less than | `#60;` | `["List#60;String#62;"]` |\n| `>` | Greater than | `#62;` | `["a #62; b"]` |\n| `\\|` | Pipe | `#124;` | `["A #124; B"]` |\n| `\\` | Backslash | `#92;` | `["C:#92;Users"]` |\n| `#` | Hash | `#35;` | `["Item #35;5"]` |\n\n### Characters That Need Encoding When They Form Shape Syntax\n\nThese are safe in `["..."]` rectangle labels but MUST be encoded when they would form a shape delimiter pattern:\n\n| Character | Name | Entity | Dangerous Context |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `(` | Open paren | `#40;` | Inside `("...")` rounded shape |\n| `)` | Close paren | `#41;` | Inside `("...")` rounded shape |\n| `[` | Open bracket | `#91;` | Inside `["..."]` when followed by patterns |\n| `]` | Close bracket | `#93;` | Before `"` could close `["..."]` prematurely |\n| `{` | Open brace | `#123;` | Inside `{"..."}` diamond shape |\n| `}` | Close brace | `#125;` | Inside `{"..."}` diamond shape |\n\n**Rule of thumb**: If the character matches the OUTER delimiter of the node shape, encode it.\n\n| Shape | Outer Delimiters | Encode These Inside |\n|---|---|---|\n| `["..."]` Rectangle | `[` `]` | `]` before `"`, `"` always |\n| `("...")` Rounded | `(` `)` | `(`, `)`, `"` |\n| `{"..."}` Diamond | `{` `}` | `{`, `}`, `"` |\n| `[("...")]` Cylinder | `[` `(` `)` `]` | `(`, `)`, `]`, `"` |\n| `(("..."))` Circle | `(` `)` | `(`, `)`, `"` |\n| `[["..."]]` Subroutine | `[` `]` | `[`, `]`, `"` |\n| `(["..."])` Stadium | `(` `[` `]` `)` | `(`, `)`, `[`, `]`, `"` |\n| `{{"..."}}` Hexagon | `{` `}` | `{`, `}`, `"` |\n\n### Characters That Are SAFE Inside `["..."]`\n\nThese do NOT need encoding when inside double-quoted rectangle labels:\n\n| Character | Name | Code (if needed elsewhere) |\n|---|---|---|\n| `:` | Colon | `#58;` |\n| `;` | Semicolon | `#59;` |\n| `.` | Period | `#46;` |\n| `,` | Comma | `#44;` |\n| `!` | Exclamation | `#33;` |\n| `?` | Question mark | `#63;` |\n| `@` | At sign | `#64;` |\n| `$` | Dollar | `#36;` |\n| `%` | Percent (single) | `#37;` |\n| `^` | Caret | `#94;` |\n| `&` | Ampersand | `#38;` |\n| `*` | Asterisk | `#42;` |\n| `+` | Plus | `#43;` |\n| `=` | Equals | `#61;` |\n| `~` | Tilde | `#126;` |\n| `_` | Underscore | `#95;` |\n| `-` | Hyphen | `#45;` |\n| `/` | Forward slash | `#47;` |\n| `\'` | Single quote | `#39;` |\n| `` ` `` | Backtick | `#96;` |\n| `§` | Section sign | `#167;` |\n| `±` | Plus-minus | `#177;` |\n\n**Note**: Even though these are safe inside `["..."]`, they may need encoding in OTHER contexts (edge labels, participant names, etc.).\n\n### The `%%` Comment Trap\n\nTwo consecutive `%` signs form a comment. If a label must contain `%%`:\n```\n✅ A["Rate: 5#37;#37; increase"]\n❌ A["Rate: 5%% increase"]    ← Parser sees comment, truncates\n```\n\nFor a single `%`, it is safe inside `["..."]`.\n\n---\n\n## Encoding in Different Diagram Contexts\n\n### Edge Labels\n```\n%% Characters in edge labels need encoding too\nA -->|"Status: #60;pending#62;"| B\nA -->|"Count #124; Total"| B\n```\n\n### Sequence Diagram Messages\nSequence diagrams use `:` as the message separator. Messages after `:` are generally safe for most characters, but encode `<`, `>`, `#` if they cause issues:\n```\nparticipant api as API\nuser ->> api: GET /items?status=active\napi -->> user: 200 OK\n```\n\n### Class Diagram Members\nUse `~` for generics instead of `<>`:\n```\nclass MyClass {\n    +List~String~ items\n    +Map~String, Integer~ counts\n}\n```\n\n### ER Diagram Labels\nRelationship labels are quoted:\n```\nCUSTOMER ||--o{ ORDER : "places"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Complex Label Examples\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    A["func#40;param#41; → result"]\n    B["Map#123;K, V#125;"]\n    C["array#91;0#93;..array#91;n#93;"]\n    D["path: C:#92;Users#92;data"]\n    E["A #60; B #62; C"]\n    F["x #124;#124; y #38;#38; z"]\n    G["Price: $19.99 #40;+tax#41;"]\n    H["Version 2.0 #35;beta"]\n\n    A --> B --> C --> D\n    E --> F --> G --> H\n```\n\nRendered labels:\n- `func(param) → result`\n- `Map{K, V}`\n- `array[0]..array[n]`\n- `path: C:\\Users\\data`\n- `A < B > C`\n- `x || y && z`\n- `Price: $19.99 (+tax)`\n- `Version 2.0 #beta`\n```\n\n---\n\n## Markdown-embedding hazards (diagram source corruption)\n\nWhen a diagram is written into a Markdown file as a ```mermaid fenced block, **some renderers run the\nfenced text through Markdown inline rules before handing it to Mermaid**, silently rewriting the\nsource. The diagram is valid on its own but throws *"Syntax error in text"* inside the document. These\nare NOT fixed by Mermaid HTML-entity encoding — the corruption happens before Mermaid sees the text.\nAvoid these tokens in the diagram body when embedding (or confirm your renderer keeps fences raw):\n\n| Token in diagram | Markdown turns it into | Where it bites | Safe alternative |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `~Type~` (class generic) | strikethrough / subscript | class diagrams (`List~Animal~`) | drop the generic — use a plain type name |\n| a *pair* of `*` | italic emphasis (`*…*`) | abstract `method()*` + `"*"` cardinality together | omit the abstract `*`; use `"many"` instead of `"*"` |\n| `_text_` | emphasis | any label | avoid leading/trailing `_`, or quote the label |\n| `[text]` | link | rarely (flowchart `["..."]` is usually safe) | keep brackets inside quotes |\n| `<x>` / `<<stereotype>>` | HTML tag / escape | class stereotypes are usually safe; bare `<x>` is not | quote labels; keep `<<abstract>>`/`<<interface>>` as-is |\n\n**Rule of thumb for generated, document-embedded diagrams:** prefer the simplest construct that conveys\nthe meaning, keep the body free of the tokens above, and **verify the rendered diagram in the target\nviewer** — not just `mermaid.parse()` or the static linter.\n',
